ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate Al3+ and Fe3+ detection mechanism of CQD, Fluorescence lifetime decay was calculated for CQD in the presence and absence of Al3+ or Fe3+ by using JOBIN-VYON Fluorolog-3-11 (HORIBA). The average life time of CQD, CQD- Al3+ and CQD- Fe3+ is shown in the Fig. 8
                        . The addition of Fe3+ in CQD decreased the fluorescence life time to 4.99 ns from 5.48 ns. The decrease in fluorescence life time of CQD- Fe3+ could be due to the electron transfer from excited CQD to unfilled orbital of Fe3+ and that further leads to the strong non radiative electron/hole recombination, which leads to the aggregation-induced emission quenching in CQD- Fe3+. However, the different scenario was observed in the case of CQD- Al3+. Fluorescence life time was increased instead of decreasing (from 5.48 ns to 5.55 ns). After comparing these results with FL responses results (Fig. 6), the following reason can be deduced that the electrostatic interaction and coordination of Al3+ ions with CQD leads to CQD- Al3+aggregates into conjugated amorphous masses, which cause the aggregation-induced high FL emission (See schematic representation in Fig. 9
                        ). More interestingly, these observations convey that as-synthesized CQD had dual fluorescence response characteristics with outstanding selectivity for Al3+ and Fe3+ions. To determine the effect of concentration on FL peak intensity, Al3+ and Fe3+ions (10- 100 μm) were added with CQD and recorded as FL spectrum are shown in Fig. 10a and b. It was observed that there is steady enhancement of FL peak intensity with concentration of Al3+ ions and decline in FL intensity with increasing Fe3+ concentration.

As shown in Fig. 11c and d, a linear plot, F/F0 vs [Q*] was obtained by plotting graph between relative intensity ratio F/F0 and concentration of Al3+ (1–6 μM). Stern–Volmer, F/F0 = 1 + KSV [Q] plot (a strong linear plot, R2 = 0.961) where, [Q*] is concentration of Al3+ ions and Ksv = 0.0285 (slope of the linear fit) was employed to measure the Limit of detection (LOD). The calculated value of Limit of detection (LOD) of Al3+ was 0.5 μM. Overall results showed that developed CQD can be applied for highly selective and sensitive detection of Fe3+ and Al3+ ions. Notably, this prominent LOD values are significantly lower than World Health Organization (WHO) guidelines value for Fe3+ (300 μM) and Al3+ (200 μM) ions and more comparable with other research works (see 
                        Table 1

                        ) [15,45,52] [68–70].
